observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management:

a) 	Ensure optimal utilization of the 20 per cent Development Fund and proper implementation of development projects funded under said fund to achieve the desirable socio-economic targets and outcomes of the LGU;

b) 	Direct the MPDC in coordination with the Municipal Development Council (MDC) and the Office of the Municipal Engineer to ensure that the identified projects to be included in the AIP which are sourced from the 20 per cent Development Fund are well-planned and procurement-and-implementation-ready;

c) 	Direct the MPDC to provide for the specific timeframe or timing of implementation for each development project rather than a uniform and generic timeframe such as January to December of a calendar year for all identified projects; and initiate the procurement procedures of these projects earlier during the calendar year rather than towards the end of the year to avoid delayed and/or non-implementation of projects;

d) 	Consider the reprogramming of continuing appropriations of unimplemented projects which may no longer be needed into other priority development projects; and

e) 	Revert the unexpended balances of continuing appropriations for fully completed projects to the unappropriated surplus of the general fund so that the same shall be made available for other priority development projects of the LGU.

We recommended that Management:

a) 	Immediately stop the charging of expenditures for the loan amortization of the two (2) units service vehicle against the 20 per cent Development Fund;

b) 	Make representations with the Development Bank of the Philippines as to the allocation of amounts of loan amortization pertaining to the two (2) units service vehicle and/or direct the Municipal Accountant to compute for its allocation based on ratio of its total cost over the loan amount, which should be excluded in the appropriations under the 20 per cent Development Fund;

c) 	Direct the Municipal Budget Officer to properly utilize the available appropriations and charged the payment of monthly loan amortizations against the respective allocated appropriations; and refrain from charging available appropriations for expenditures not intended for;

d) 	Direct the MPDC to specify the nature and amount of loan amortization in the Annual Investment Plan and Annual Budget under the 20 per cent Development Fund, and exclude the allocation of loan amortization for the two (2) units service vehicle from the said fund; and

e) 	Strictly adhere with the provisions under DBM-DOF-DILG JMC No. 1 s. 2020 particularly item 3.2.5 on the expenditures which are not allowed to be charged against the 20 per cent Development Fund.

We recommended the following:

a) 	The Local Chief Executive, thru the Human Resource Management Officer (HRMO), formulate a uniform policy or guidelines in the hiring of JO/COS personnel taking into consideration the LGU’s existing organizational structure, plantilla of personnel, service requirements, financial capability and existing COA, CSC and DBM rules and regulations; and endorse the same to the Office of the Sangguniang Bayan for legislation;

b) 	The Sangguniang Bayan, upon review and deliberation, institutionalize the policy or guidelines in the hiring of JO/COS personnel by legislating it into an ordinance;

c) 	The Management revisit and assess its existing organizational structure in order to establish the number of personnel needed or necessary in each office/department, and evaluate whether the duties and responsibilities of the hired JO/COS personnel correlates with the principal mandate of the assigned office/department, to avoid the hiring of excessive and/or unnecessary number of JO/COS personnel;

d) 	The Management require the recording of attendance of JO/COS personnel in the existing biometrics system of the LGU, especially those assigned within or near the premises of the Municipal Hall. Otherwise, at least require the recording of attendance in permanent logbooks for JO/COS personnel assigned in the field or far from the premises of the Municipal Hall, indicating their names and signatures as well as the time of arrival at and departure from their place of assignment;

e) 	The HRMO, in coordination with respective Heads of Offices/Departments, properly monitor and validate the attendance and actual accomplishments of JO/COS personnel; 

f) 	The Local Chief Executive and/or the Municipal Vice Mayor use the appropriate form of or type of contract or agreement in the hiring of JO personnel which includes the signature of the concerned JO personnel as acceptance or acknowledgment of the stipulations of the job order contract or agreement;

g) 	The Management pay the services of JO personnel using a daily salary rate instead of a monthly salary rate; and

h) 	The HRMO carry out a periodic orientation/reorientation for JO/COS personnel on various rules and regulations on human resource, as well as, the terms and agreements of their employment.

Recommendation:
We recommended that Management:
Send demand letters to concerned accountable officers and employees with unsettled accounts for their immediate settlement. In case of non-settlement of employees who are still in active service with the LGU despite demand, cause the withholding of salaries or any money claims due them and/or file appropriate charges against them;
Take appropriate actions on the unsettled accounts of accountable officers who are not in active service with the LGU and external debtors;
Request for write-off of dormant accounts in accordance with existing COA rules and regulations;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to examine the accounts with abnormal/negative balances, and effect the necessary adjustments, if warranted;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to prepare the Schedules of Dormant Accounts quarterly and submit the same to the Office of the Auditor or before the 15th day of the ensuing month; and
Direct the Municipal Accountant to disclose comparative information in the Notes to Financial Statements relative to the dormant accounts of the LGU.

Recommendation:
We recommended the following:
The Local Chief Executive include the conduct of semestral physical count of inventories on hand and the preparation and submission of the Report on the Physical Count of Inventories (RPCI) as part of the duties and responsibilities of the Inventory Committee;
The Inventory Committee conduct semestral physical count of inventories and submit the result of the physical count using the RPCI to the Office of the Auditor not later than July 31 and January 31 of each year for the first and second semesters, respectively;
The General Services Officer prepare and maintain stock cards for each supply/inventory and periodically reconcile the same with the accounting records and the result of the physical count;
The Municipal Accountant prepare and maintain supply ledger cards for each supply/inventory and periodically reconcile the same with the property records and the result of the physical count;
The Municipal Accountant observe the Perpetual Inventory Method by initially recording the purchases of supplies and materials as inventories and subsequently recognize the same as expenses upon issuance/distribution to end-users/intended beneficiaries; and
The Municipal Accountant provide appropriate disclosures in the notes to financial statements relative to the amount of inventory recognized as expenses during the year pursuant to Paragraph 47 of IPSAS 12.

Recommendation:
We recommended the following:
The Local Chief Executive reconstitute the LGU’s Inventory Committee to include at least one member from the Municipal Accounting Office or issue a supplemental Executive Order designating an official or employee from said office to be a member of the existing Inventory Committee;
Management take full opportunity on the application of COA Circular No. 2020-006 and fully comply with the prescribed guidelines and procedures, particularly the conduct of physical count of PPE, the recognition of PPE items found at station, the disposition of non-existing/missing PPE items, the procedures in the derecognition of non-existing/missing PPEs without available record of accountability, and the recording of accounting entries and disclosures in the notes to financial statements, for the purpose of one-time cleansing of PPE account balances of the LGU;
The Inventory Committee conduct annual physical count of PPE to facilitate the preparation and submission of RPCPPE not later than January 31 of each year, complete with all the required information, which shall serve as the basis for the reconciliation and updating of accounting and property records;
The Municipal Accountant prepare and maintain complete PPE Ledger Cards, and reconcile the same with the property records and the results of the physical count; and
The General Services Officer prepare and maintain complete Property Cards, and reconcile the same with the accounting records and the results of the physical count.

Recommendation:
We recommended the following:
The Municipal Engineer furnish the Municipal Accountant copies of the Certificate of Completion, approved program of works and other pertinent documents as basis for the reclassification of accounts for the completed projects;
The Municipal Engineer observe the timely submission of pertinent documents pertaining to completed projects as basis of the Municipal Accountant to record the same at year-end and for the proper setting-up of accounts payable equivalent to the unpaid balances to contractors;
The Municipal Accountant prepare the necessary adjusting entries to properly reclassify the completed infrastructure assets from the CIP accounts to the appropriate PPE accounts; and to recognize the accounts payable equivalent to the amount due to contractors, as applicable;
The Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Engineer conduct reconciliation of documents/records pertaining to the CIP accounts amounting to P5.364 million, recorded in the books of accounts but were not included in the Status Report of PPAs prepared by the Municipal Engineer; and
The Municipal Accountant, in coordination with the Municipal Engineer, exert efforts to trace back prior years’ records and identify the unidentified balances of CIP accounts amounting to P14.049 million and/or derecognize these account balances, if warranted, following the guidelines and procedures for the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts prescribed under COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020.

Recommendation:
We recommended the following:
The GSO prepare the IIRUP, and submit the same to the Disposal Committee for inspection, appraisal and disposal of the identified unserviceable properties. The GSO coordinate with the Municipal Accountant in providing relevant information in the IIRUP such as the accumulated depreciation, accumulated impairment losses, if any, carrying amount and other remarks for each unserviceable property;
The Management, thru the Local Chief Executive, create a Disposal Committee whose functions include the inspection, appraisal and disposal of unserviceable properties in accordance to COA and DBM Joint Circular No. 2024-1 dated January 30, 2024;
The Disposal Committee, after its creation, conduct inspection and appraisal and set the final appraised values of all unserviceable properties subject for disposal, as identified and reported in the IIRUP. The appraised values shall be considered as the minimum selling price so that the LGU will receive fair compensation for the items sold;
The Management submit to the Office of the Auditor a written letter, together with the IIRUP, appraisal report and other pertinent documents, requesting for technical evaluation of the appraised values of the unserviceable properties as determined by the Disposal Committee, which will be endorsed by the latter to the COA IX Technical Audit Group for their independent evaluation;
The Disposal Committee determine the appropriate mode of disposal and undertake the disposal proceedings in accordance with the revised manual on the disposal of government properties; and
The Management exert efforts in locating pertinent documents relative to the disposal of the three units heavy equipment and 1 unit motor vehicle with total cost of P4.492 million as basis for the Municipal Accountant to derecognize these PPEs from the books of accounts of the LGU, and/or derecognize these account balances, if warranted, following the guidelines and procedures for the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts prescribed under COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020.

