Recommendation:
We recommended that Management in coordination with the Municipal Solid Waste Management Board (MSWMB):
Review/revisit the SWM Plan and incorporate the PPAs indicated therein such as the establishment of sanitary landfill in the LGU’s Annual Investment Plan and provide appropriate funding for the same;
Stop the operation of the open dumpsite for its waste disposal and consider other solid waste management alternatives such as effective and efficient implementation of re-use, recycle and composting programs and/or the establishment of sanitary landfill as its final disposal site;
Improve the separate containment area for special wastes or household hazardous wastes in such a way that the area is not left open and exposed to the people with access to the Eco-Park;
Consult with the EMB on the use and operation of plastic shredders and conduct coordination with associations, cooperatives, other bodies and constituents of the municipality on the distribution and acceptance of re-usable plastic wastes processed thru plastic shredders;
Improve the supply of electricity in the Eco-Park for the operationalization of the bio composter and/or relocate the same to another area where there is stable supply of electricity; and
Regularly monitor the status of the SWM Plan, review any deficiencies and ensure its sustainability, viability, effectiveness and relevance.

We recommended the following:

a) 	The Municipal Accountant conduct analysis of the Accounts Payable, prepare the necessary adjusting entries to reclassify some accounts payable into its appropriate liability accounts;

b) 	The Management determine the validity of accounts pertaining to terminal leave benefits, prioritize and/or cause the immediate payment or release of funds, as warranted; 

c) 	The Management determine the validity of all accounts particularly those accounts under the Trust Fund which are without particulars/descriptions; and 

d) 	The Management cause the reversion of accounts which remained outstanding for over two (2) years and for which no actual claim has been filed, or which is not covered by perfected contracts on record, or for which the purpose of the trust fund has already been accomplished.

We recommended the following:

a) 	The Management refrain from granting cash advance for PCF to elected officials;

b) 	The Municipal Accountant ensure completeness of documentary requirements in the grant of cash advance for PCF such as copy of authority from the Municipal Mayor, approved estimates of petty expenses for the month, and approved fidelity bond, as applicable;

c) 	The Municipal Accountant ensure the completeness of documentary requirements in the disbursement of petty cash replenishments;

d) 	The Petty Cash Custodians comply with the requirement for replenishment of the PCF when the disbursements reach at least 75%, or as the need requires;

e) 	The Petty Cash Custodians refrain from charging regular expenses such as rentals, subscriptions, light and water bills and the like out of PCF; and

f) 	The Petty Cash Custodians fully liquidate their cash advance for PCF at year-end by submitting a Report of Disbursements and its supporting documents and return the unused cash, if any, to the Municipal Treasurer who shall issue an Official Receipt which will be attached to the liquidation.

We recommended that Management:

a)	Send demand letters to concerned accountable officers and employees with unsettled accounts for its immediate settlement. In case of non-settlement of employees who are still connected with the LGU, cause the withholding of salaries or any money claims due them;

b)	Take appropriate actions on the unsettled accounts of accountable officers who are no longer connected or not in active service with the LGU; 

c)	Request for write-off of dormant accounts pursuant to COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016; 


d)	Direct the Municipal Accountant to examine the accounts with abnormal/negative balances, and effect the necessary adjustments, if warranted; and

e)	Direct the Municipal Accountant to reclassify accounts of AOs who are no longer connected or not in active service with the LGU into Other Receivables account for fair presentation in the financial statements in compliance with the Revised Chart of Accounts provided under COA Circular No. 2015-002.

We recommended that Management:

a)	Conduct verification, analysis, and validation of the balances of the Due to NGAs accounts, determine the source agencies and the status of programs, projects and activities for which funds were received; and maintain complete records of the same;

b)	Direct the Municipal Accountant to reconcile the balances of Due to NGAs account with the balances of concerned source agencies, and effect the necessary adjustments, as warranted;

c)	Make representations with identified source agencies for the return of unutilized balances related to completed projects;

d)	Make representations with the DA and the Department of Budget and Management on the release of the remaining funds in relation to the completed projects under the DA-PAMANA Program; and

e)	Make representations with the source agencies on the necessary actions to be taken for funds received but for which intended programs, projects, and activities remain unimplemented, or if implemented, were not completed or abandoned.

We recommended the following:

a)	Management established strong internal controls in the handling of cash particularly the collections and remittances from the Collectors to the Municipal Treasurer, and the collections and deposits made by the Municipal Treasurer to the AGDB, to prevent further incurrence of unrecorded collections and/or over-deposit of collections, which resulted to abnormal/negative balances of the Cash Local Treasury account;

b)	The Municipal Accountant make representations with concerned government agencies relative to the refund of erroneous or over-remittances made. In case refund is not granted and no other course of action can be taken, the Municipal Accountant refund the said amounts;

c)	The Municipal Accountant exert effort in identifying the forwarded negative balances of Due to PhilHEALTH account under the General Fund and Economic Enterprise; and

d)	The Municipal Accountant properly monitor the withholding and remittance of mandatory contributions so as to avoid under/over-remittance of contributions; and review thoroughly the schedule of payables due to concerned agencies during the month and that remittance shall be based on actual contributions vis-a-vis payroll deductions.

We recommended that Management:

a)	Direct the General Services Officer and the Municipal Accountant to reconcile their records pertaining to the subject unserviceable heavy equipment and motor vehicles particularly the cost and carrying amounts of these PPE items, which will be subsequently dropped from the books of accounts after its disposal;

b)	Make representation with the Provincial Government of Zamboanga del Sur relative to the disposal of unserviceable heavy equipment, which were unrecorded in the books of accounts of the Municipality, and were identified as owned by the former;

c)	Direct the Property Unit to prepare the IIRUP for all unserviceable property, and the WMR for all waste materials, subject for disposal;

d)	Create a committee responsible for the appraisal of unserviceable property and supplies, whose appraisal shall be considered as the floor price in the case of disposal thru sale at public auction; and

e)	Direct the General Services Officer to dispose of the unserviceable property and supplies in accordance with the rules and regulations on supply and property management in local government units.

